---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const description = "What to do when credit bureaus verify, reject, or ignore your medical debt dispute. Response scripts for every outcome.";
---

<Base title="Bureau Response Scripts — CreditCookbook" description="{description}" posterTitle="BUREAU RESPONSE" posterLabel="// 11 — handling bureau responses">
  <section class="section" data-animate>
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label" data-animate>// content</span>
      <h2 style="margin-bottom: 24px;">Bureau response scripts</h2>
      <p style="max-width: 64ch; margin-bottom: 32px;">After you dispute a medical collection, the bureau has 30 days to investigate. Their response determines your next move. Here's what to do for every possible outcome.</p>

<h3 style="margin-bottom: 16px;">Outcome 1: Item removed</h3>
<p style="max-width: 60ch; margin-bottom: 24px;">The best case. The bureau could not verify the account and removed it. Check your updated credit report to confirm it's gone. No further action needed — move on to the next dispute.</p>

<h3 style="margin-bottom: 16px;">Outcome 2: Item verified (not removed)</h3>
<p style="max-width: 60ch; margin-bottom: 16px;">The bureau claims they verified the account. Don't give up — this is common and often based on automated e-OSCAR verification, not actual investigation.</p>
<ol style="margin-left: 24px; line-height: 2.5; margin-bottom: 24px;">
  <li><strong>Send a Method of Verification (MOV) letter.</strong> Demand to know exactly how the bureau verified the account — who they contacted, what documentation was provided.</li>
  <li><strong>File a CFPB complaint.</strong> Go to consumerfinance.gov and file a complaint against the bureau. This forces a real investigation.</li>
  <li><strong>Dispute with the furnisher directly.</strong> Under FCRA § 1681s-2(b), you can dispute directly with the entity that reported the account.</li>
  <li><strong>Send a 609 letter.</strong> Request all documents the bureau used to verify, under FCRA § 609.</li>
</ol>

<h3 style="margin-bottom: 16px;">MOV Letter Template</h3>
<div class="mono-block" data-animate style="margin-bottom: 32px;">
[YOUR NAME]
[YOUR ADDRESS]

[DATE]

[BUREAU NAME]
[BUREAU ADDRESS]

RE: Method of Verification Request
Account: [ACCOUNT NUMBER]
Dispute Date: [DATE YOU DISPUTED]

To Whom It May Concern,

You verified the above-referenced account after my
dispute dated [DATE]. I am requesting the method of
verification you used, as required by FCRA Section 611
(15 U.S.C. Section 1681i(a)(6)(B)(iii)).

Specifically, I want to know:
1. The name and contact information of the person or
   entity who verified this account.
2. The documentation that was provided to verify the
   accuracy of this account.
3. Whether this verification was performed
   electronically (e-OSCAR) or manually.

If you cannot provide this information, the
verification was insufficient and I demand removal.

Sincerely,

[YOUR NAME]
</div>

<h3 style="margin-bottom: 16px;">Outcome 3: No response (ignored)</h3>
<p style="max-width: 60ch; margin-bottom: 24px;">If the bureau doesn't respond within 30 days, they are in violation of FCRA § 1681i. The item must be removed. Send a demand letter citing the violation and file a CFPB complaint.</p>

<h3 style="margin-bottom: 16px;">Outcome 4: Item updated but not removed</h3>
<p style="max-width: 60ch;">Sometimes the bureau "updates" the account (changes the status, balance, or date) instead of removing it. If the update is still inaccurate, re-dispute with the corrected information. If the account was paid, cite the 45-day paid removal rule.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
